betterquesting:10.desc:8:
I know I've been super nice and have given you all the water purification supplies you've needed up to this point, but it stops now!

Not the niceness, 'cause we're friends.

It's about time you made your own charcoal filters though.

For this, you'll also need to make some paper from sugar cane. For all the ways to make paper, check out JEI. If you don't know what JEI is then go back and check out the §eSuch a User§r quest.

If you haven't found some already, you should be able to find it growing on the bank of a body of water.

§nTask 1§r: Make paper.
§nTask 2§r: Make a charcoal filter.

The title pretty much says it all.

This is how you upgrade your tool belt.

§nTask 1§r: Make a belt pouch.

You found a waystone and tried to use it without even knowing what you were getting into. This sounds about right, for someone wandering through the Block Rock Desert.

Waystones sometimes appear at villages, and sometimes in other places too. Once you get far enough along you can make them on your own. Travel past a certain distance (or between dimensions) will cost you XP. 

As your reward you can choose between your own waystone (choose where you place it carefully!) or a warpscroll is a single use item which will allow you to go to any waystone you have activated. To use the warp scroll hold down right click until the memu pops up.
waystones are cool if you can find some ender eyes
Potions are a thing. Potions are a lovely thing that you should consider brewing up. The brewing stand takes some bottles and something to heat. It is fu eled with blaze powder.

We are going to use a lot of wire. It is used to make comlpicated machines and it's used to attach machines together for power transfer. 

Eventually we won't have to cut it all by hand.

For now, cut some copper by hand. You will need wire cutters.

betterquesting:10.name:8: we are all matter out of place
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
It happens in the multiverse. Something goes wrong, and you die. In this particular corner of the multiverse the penalty isn't that bad. So long as you can find your tombstone...

You should see a new beacon visible on the horizon. You can also see the beacon on your JourneyMap (opens with "j" by default). Go there and you should see a tombstone nearby. In most case the tombstone will appear however it may be very difficult to get to. Like if you ended up in a lava ocean, or fell out the bottom of the world.

If you right click the tombstone it will tell you who it belongs to. To retrieve your items, destroy the tombstone. It is quicker with a pickaxe. Note that your items may end up scattered about when you destroy the tombstone. If you died somewhere hazardous (like in a lava ocean) you should ensure there is ample enclosed space to help keep your items safe. You will end up with your tombstone as a memento of what happened.

Try to not become moop again.

It all starts with inferium essence. This. with the occasoinal prosperity shard, provides the basis of mystical agriculture. This mod allows you to create plants which produce their own form of resource-specific essence. These plants are tiered based on how complex the resource is. Water and dirt are easy to create, but to grow gold you will need a lot of inferium essence just to craft the seed itself. These crops are probably the easiest, if not quickest, path to full automated luxury queer block utopias.

Inferium may be found mixed in with hematite, malachite, and coal. Prosperity shards show up in veins of gold and quartz.

This special kind of fertilizer only works on mystical agriculture crops.

Alright, class! Today we're learning how to make leather!

Check JEI for all the ways you can make leather but the best early game method is combining four rabbit skins in a crafting table. If you are feeling flush with food, you can also use a Drying Rack and hang out some cooked meat (such as rabbit). If you don't remember what JEI is then go back and check the early §eSuch a User§r quest. It covers a lot of important game tools such as the map, JEI, and others!

Your reward includes a new piece of gameplay lore on some of the possibilities you have for customizing your avatar.

Inferium essence can be found in Inferium Ore or grown from an Inferium Seed. These seeds are tiered, with each tier above one producing more essence per harvest. You can improve the growth rate using mystical fertilizer, and a little bit with the watering can, normal bone meal based fertilizer have no effect. The sprinkler does have an effect.

Make some water, grow some water.

The Mystical Agriculture crops all produce various forms of essence. You can then craft this essense into actual resources.

Four water essense in the cardinal directions around a bucket will craft a bucket of water.

There is some content within the Tribes That May Be multiverse which crosses back and forth between realities.

Things such as external tools and services which may be used to extend the Block Rock Desert experience, or resources which the player may (or may not) find valuable.

We aren't going to force these upon you.

If you would like these quests to be accessible then must explicitly consent.

But if you do, there is no going back.

It ain't easy having a good time and one of the ways this manifests is by having to learn. Your trusty guidebook will get you only so far. The Tribes That May Be multiverse is full of guides, manuals, and books. While you can easily make book shelves to keep them on, we often want to keep some of these books close at hand.

Enter the Akashik Tome. You can add (many but not all) books to it by combining them (one at a time) with your Akashik Tome in a crafting grid. Access the stored books by right clicking on empty space with the Akashik Tome in your hand.

You will be presented with a list of books in the tome. Select one and then yor tome will turn into that book. When you are done, left click on empty space with the book selected. To remove a particular book from the tome, select it, and then drop it (default "q" while crouching (default "shift").

Not every book can be stored in the Akashik tome. You can make book cases for easy wall storage of books.
Some words about fuel generation and how hard it is I guess

There is no shortage of furniture for storing your things. But some of the furniture is classier than others.

The nightstand is one of those.

You don't have to put it next to your bed, but why wouldn't you?

It's classier that way.

betterquesting:10.name:8: When all you have is a hammer...
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
There are a lot of things you can do with a hammer. In this multiverse zone trip, the Immersive Engineering hammer is used to adjust blocks. You can use it to rotate supported blocks, and configure a variety of Immersive Engineering things such as flood lights and capacitors.

Craft an Immersive Engineering hammer.

betterquesting:10.name:8: To Do or Not To Do
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Clipboard are rad. If you keep down the path of exploring the Block Rock Desert then you will end up with lots of things on your todo list, lots of places to come back to and explore, lots of things to craft.

Write them down on your clipboard! It features multiple tabs and may be placed on a wall for all to view with right click.

There are several types of motorized vehicles which may be created at the vehicle workstation. In order to make a vehicle, you are going to need a decent amount of ore, redstone, and some specialized items. You can take your pick of electric or combustion engine as your reward. You will need to create a wheel (only actually need one, not four, because reasons) before you can make your first vehicle.

To use the vehicle workstation, place it in world and then right click on it. You can scroll through the available options and see the resources required. There is an optional space for a dye as well, if you would like a more vibrant ride.

The result of your crafting will be a vehicle crate. Place this down and then tap the top of it with the wrench. This will result in your sweet ride. 

Now where to find fuel....

There are three different sizes of speakers that you can build. Let's start with the smallest. You are going to need some nether quartz and a diamond for this, but don't worry - these can both be found in the Block Rock Desert.

Once you have created your speaker you can attach it to a record player or a radio with speaker wire. To do so, select the speaker wire. You can then right click on the source block (radio or record player) and then right click on the speaker. Note that the speaker wires don't go very far - only about 7 blocks.

You can remove speaker wire by using wire cutters on the speaker or source block.

Why stop with just one hammer? If you want to repair vehicles you find or make, you are going to need at least one more...

Craft a hammer from the MrCrafyfish Vehicles mod.

We are going to need clay. Probably a lot of clay, especially if you want to make your house out of brick. Which is absolutely a choice you could make.

Lots of things are made out of clay. Cooking utensils, flower pots, along with crafting equipment.

Find some clay! You can usually find it underground.
There are better records in this modpack. I shold write some words about that later.

Now that you've got a bucket, I've got a trick to teach you.

You can use it to purify even §omore§r water.

But! Now that said pure water is in a bucket, you can fill an external vessel with it to prepare for longer treks across the dusty, dusty wasteland...

§nTask 1§r: Fill your bucket with water.
§nTask 2§r: Purify the water in your bucket by heating it in your furnace.

Tips!
You can not only put your purified water in a storage vessel with your bucket, but also take it out the same way.
This will help you refill your canteen on the go.

Alright, the time for hand holding is just about over.

From now on, the quests are going to get pared down to only the essentials.

Being that it's almost time to leave in search of a suitable home and the fact that you've gotten this far, I'm sure you can manage.

But how are you supposed to get where you're going with all the possessions you've surely gathered by now?

Well, unless you want to practice extreme minimalism and discard everything you own, you're going to need a backpack.

§
§n§n§r§nTask 1§r: Make yourself a backpack.

*The crate you receive as a reward for this quest will keep its contents when picked up, making it perfect for travel.

*Will incorporate some of duplicate quest text;

It takes a lot of supplies and preparation to have a good time. You are going to need more than your pockets and your tool belt. The simple backpack can be upgrade as you gain access to more advanced materials. Always make sure to empty it before you upgrade!

To put it on, bring up your inventory (default key "e"). Click on the baubles icon (a little ring in the upper right of your avatar display). Shift-click the backpack and you will now be wearing it (assuming nothing was already in the back slot). When you are wearing it as a bauble you can open it via a hotkey (default "b").

betterquesting:10.name:8: Every day is hump day when you're a camel. <3

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
If you're feeling like you could use a another pocket or two to put something nifty in, a tool belt could be the answer.

So... uh... make one.

§nTask 1§r: Make a tool belt.

*You can upgrade this as you progress, so don't dismiss it so readily based on its currently limited capacity.

Copied text;
There are a lot of tools and widgets to juggle as we stumble through autonomous zone to autonomous zone. A great way to  hold them is with a toolbelt! As common in the Block Rock Desert as throughout the multiverse. As much a fashion statement as they are practical.

You can craft one with leather, iron, and string. Out of the box, they can hold two items. Using an anvil you cand slap more tool pouches on to your belt and hold up to nine things!

To add something to your toolbelt, have the item you want to place into your toolbelt selected in your hotbar and press "R" (default key). You will then be presented with a selection wheel and if the toolbelt is not full, select insert. To remove something from your toolbelt, have an empty slot on your hotbar selected, and again press "R". Select the item you wish to extract.

You've officially proven yourself ready to venture out into the world and make a home for yourself. Make a compass, so you can find your way back to where you entered the desert. If for no other reason than to welcome others who join you in this place as they arrive.

In an effort to facilitate your next chaptert, I've provided you with some magical fruit. Given it's very perculiar taste, you will need to have Magic skilled up to 2.

Once you eat the fruit, you'll be able to fly for a limited time (indicated by a countdown timer at the top-right corner of your view).

Be wise about how you use this boon and don't fly too high, lest you fall to your demise.

*
To enable/disable §3creative flight§r, double-tap the §3§5space bar§r.

Architecturecraft is one of several mods included specifically to allow you to make things prettier. It allows for the shaping of almost any block into columns, window frames, roofing tiles, and other things.

You can use the Finishing Hammer to rotate these modified blocks after they have been placed.

Most hand tools are going to get made in the Smeltery. It's a piece of crafting equipment that is comprised of multiple blocks put together in a particular way.

You are going to need a lot of clay, sand, and gravel.

You didn't bring enough food to last in this endless desert and eating cooked rabbit will get boring quickly.

Time to start the camp kitchen.

Craft some cooking utensils.

As a reward you get either a tool rack for storing your kitchen tools, or a fruit basken to keep fruit in!

Let's start making some fancier tools. Almost every hand tool, or weapon, you will want to use will be created using Tinkers Construct. It involves a few pieces of creafting equipment. You have already made the crafting station. You will probably want to read the manual - Materials and You - to get a better handle on how Tinkers Construct works.

Craft a stencil table and a part builder. You can use these for making custom tools, and you will want them as you get into the smeltery to make fancyier custom tools.

For your reward you can choose between a pattern chest and a part chest. These are purpose built storage items for the little fiddly bits you will end up with as part of a Tinkers workshop.

The Big Book allows you to keep notes or write stories. You can write up to 256 pages and eight different tabbed sections. There is control over the text formatting as well. You can save and edit at any time.

If you ever decide that the book is finished then you can sign it and then mass produce it if you would like. Note that a signed book may not be edited any more, and you cannot undo signing.

The Smeltery is going to be your friend. You will use it to make other friends - tools, weapons, and armore that you can upgrade, repair, and name. Before you go too far down this path make sure to read the manual - Materials and You.

You should have enough material to make a 3x3x2 smeltery with two drains, one tank, a casting table, and a casting basin.

You should construct it somewhere safe.

At this point you have probably discovered that you can jump and you can fall. You can't jump very far, but you can fall quite far, depending on local geography. There are several things you can do to change how this works.

Stairs are pretty handy for going between floors of your house, or down into the mines.

Ladders are quite functional however you do need to be a little agile to use make (if not use) them.

As a reward, you get a step ladder! You can't use it without being a little bit agile though. Under your inventory screen (e by default but we should know that by now) on the left hand side you will find the "skiils" tab. When you click this you have a skill selection screen. You will need to have a 2 in agility to use the step ladder. Note that you scroll up and down the skills screen with the mouse wheel (or track pad).

The step ladder is equally handy for hanging fairy lights as it is reaching the top of trees you are chopping down.

The step ladder is pretty neat but sometimes you need a bit of an extra reach. The rope ladder can be placed on the edge of a cliff, or at the top of a cavern, or along the side of a wall. It will drop down as far as it can (based on how much rope ladder you have in your inventory). You do need to be a bit more agile to use this than the step ladder.

Equally as handy for rescuing people who have fallen down wells as it is for dropping into mystical caverns from the roof.

There are plenty of ladders in this world and they all pretty much work the same. You will travel faster in some of them (such as the ones from the Engineers Decor mod) if you look up or down.

The step ladder gives you a bit of an extra step, and the rope ladder can help you get into places in a pinch.

Scaffolding is for building things. The basic scaffolding can be built off of itself, but will decay over time. It's pretty cheap to make so you can go all out.

As you progress into the realm of fully automated queer block utopia you will gain access to more permanent scaffolding made out of creosote treated wood and steel.

But for now, you can use the varios scaffoldings provided by the Cyclic mod in order to help you build things.

Well you've found a place that is probably going to be your home for now. Time to start collecting things!

 There are a variety of other simple chests which may be constructed using regional woods. There is an amazing about of flexibility in terms of how you can store stuff but it generally all starts with a simple wooden chest.

Chests can be placed next to each other to double in size in an aesthetically pleasing way. You can make increasingly larger chests (and other things for storage) as you progress.

As a reward, you get an upgrade to expand the size of a single chest.

If you are the kind of logistics fetishist I think you are then some of the first todo items on your clipboard are related to sustainably storing the rapidly escalating amount of blocks you have collected. Storage Drawers are a great way of doing so and they can be expanded, upgraded,  and are compatible with advanced tech.

The framing table may be used with framed drawers to use any kind of wood for your drawers. You can actually mix and match the different kinds of wood as well to make patterns if you would like.

We've talked about the questbook and how helpful it is to your adventure but what other books are there?

You may have noticed that you started out with a Journal. Throughout your time in the multiverse you will find bits and pieces of lore. As you collect these they will end up in your journal and you can read them.

Some lore will be part of the story, some lore will be the stories of others, and some will be informative and help you learn about difference pieces of the Tribes That May Be experience.

If you are ever confused about where to head next, or how to do a think you are pretty sure you learned, then always remember to take a look at your journal if your trusty quest book doesn't have any clues.
It ain't a real party without some blinky lights. You can attach the strobe light, laser, and laser cluster to a source block (such as a radio or record player) using speaker wire.

Once you get locked into a serious vinyl collection the tendency is to take it as far as you can.

The Disc Holder can be used to hold all kinds of records, along with frequency crystals.

It looks a lot classier than a milk crate.

With the Cooking for Blockheads book you can take a look through all the different food recipes for ingredients you are currently holding. Eventually, you can make a full kitchen with built in storage and the ability to easily make varied foods.

Eventually...

The sleeping bag is OK but it's not quite the same as a proper bed. A normal bed will set a home location for you, so you end up going back there when you die. Without a bed, you will end up back in D-Lot when you die, and nobody wants that.

Craft a bed, place it somewhere you want to wake up in. After either a restfull nights sleep, or death. Both are inevitable.

You can also place two beds side by side, if that fits your lifestyle and/or aesthetic.

The only thing better than a good nights sleep is spending the day in a hammock.

To hang a hammock you need two rope & nails. And some hammock cloth. And some trees.

You can place the role and nail into some logs. Trees make a good target. Make sure there is a straight line between them (along the N/S or E/W axis). Once you've done that, right click with the hammock cloth on one of the nails. The max distance is about five blocks. Note that while you can put the nails in other blocks, you can't make a hammock that way.

Sweet day dreams.

Another way to spend the day or night is in a comfortable couch. You can place multiple couch pieces side by side to make sweet sectionals.

You can make different colors of couch by dying your wool prior to making the couch.
A nice coffee table helps bring the room together. You can place items on the coffee table, like books.

You may have noticed all the dry gardens all over this desert. Chances are you've broken some and gotten some things from them. You can use these things, along with various kitchen implements, to craft real food. Before you can do this quest, you need to have started a garden - look under the Post Scarcity quest line.

Make some fruit salad and make some garden soup.

Enjoy your fruit salad and savor your garden soup.

To start using the records you have found, you are going to need a record player. The record player has a small speaker built-in but if you are going to throw a serious party then you will want to build some larger speakers.

While it's fun to shuffle around records in a block world, streaming in outside sources can also be nice. The Better Records Radio can be used with tuned frequency crystals to bring mp3 streams into minecraft.

You will need at least three frequency crystals - one for the Frequency Tuner, one for the Radio, and one to tune to a radio station.

To use the frequency tuner, place it in world and right click on it. You can then specify a name and a URL to an icecast2 stream. Once those are in place, put the crystal in the tuning slot and click "Tune". Note that only icecast2 streams are supported.

Once you have a tuned crystal, you can place it in the radio. Shift right click on the radio with an empty hand to open/close. When the radio is open, right click with a tuned frequency crystal to start the music. Right click on the radio open radio with a frequency crystal and an empty hand will cause the crystal to be ejected.

You can use a record inscriber to encode a HTTP url containing a mp3 into a record. I think it also works with ogg files?

Anyway, the default Better Records configuration in the Tribes That May Be modpack supports mp3's up to 800mb (bc some sets go into the sunrise) and should start playing the music as it is downloading.

Your mileage may vary.

You're finally here! It's true.

But where's everyone else?

Well, at least you've got me, your trusty quest book.

In case it isn't obvious, your current priority is survival.

First, try to remember what color your sleeping bag is and §5l-click§r §""§2Claim§r".

Next, exit my interface and take stock of your inventory.

Also, be sure to take a look at the quest "Such A User..." for some helpful info and a free goody.

The "Dear Journal" quest introduces your journal,  as invaluable a companion as me, your trusty quest book.

The human body is generally anywhere from 50-78% water.

You should probably try to stay somewhere in that range if you'd like to survive.

Keep an eye on those little water drops at the bottom of your field of view to make sure you don't turn into a dusty little piece of jerky.

§nTask 1§r: Drink some water from your canteen.

betterquesting:10.name:8: So much for shade in the desert...
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
That is how Minecraft generally starts.

You punch a tree, alive or dead, until you get something useful. It's often, but not always, a log.

Then you make planks out of the log with your §obare, hands§r (or the 2x2 grid in your inventory).

Finally, before you know it you're being chased through a darkened desert by coyotes.

For the moment being, let's just stick to getting a crafting station built.

§nTask 1§r: Punch a tree until you get a log.
§n§nTask 2§r: Turn that log into planks.
§nTask 3§r: Make those planks into a crafting table.
§nTask 4§r: Turn that crafting table into a crafting station.

Moving a drawer full of thousands of pieces of cobblestone, or pieces of flesh, or beer, or whatever you keep in your drawers - it sounds terrible.

You should make some packing tape. You can seal up a set of storage drawers by right clicking on it with the tape. You can then safely break the drawers with an axe and move it.

You should probably find a water source and use it to fill your canteen.

You can do this by §9crouch§ring + §9r-click§ring on a water block with your canteen in hand.

If it's an emergency situation, you can drink straight from standing water by doing the same thing with an empty hand, but you probably shouldn't do too much of that...

But fret not, thirsty wanderer, you can purify the water in a canteen with the handy charcoal filters you got.

All you need to do is combine your full canteen and a charcoal filter in a §2crafting grid§r to get some pure, tasty, H20.

§nTask 1§r: Refill your canteen and purify the water inside.

There is a lot of mining and crafting in Minecraft (never would've guessed from the name, right?).

Even in this particular Minecraft multiverse you'll need to do a significant amount of both before we can get to fully-automated, luxury, queer-block socialism.

It will take a bit of work to get there, and as you progress you will need to improve not only your tools, but the skills necessary to use them as well.

§
§n§r§nTask 1§r: Make your first pickaxe!

*As you gain experience, make sure to check the skills tab of your inventory to allocate the experience you'll be getting.

That trusty knife of yours is great and all, but let's be real... you should probably find a way to better defend yourself.

It's about time you armed yourself with §mknowledge!§r some sort of weapon.

To the right, you'll see a few different options for swords, some of which you may have the materials on hand for already. Different materials (and there are a lot of options) will have different strenghts and in some cases special effects.

You should probably have a helmet too, now that you're thinking of running around swinging a weapon at things that can fight back...

I've got you covered. <3

§nTask 1§r: Craft one of the listed swords.

You will eventually fill up your drawers. Fortunately they can be upgraded for more storage, or more features.

Let's start with more storage.

Craft a basic storage upgrade.

Two things;

§nTask 1§r: Mine blocks.
§nTask 2§r: Make a furnace.

§l§r§lQuick Tip:
§rIf you mine down far enough, you'll find "bedrock". Bedrock looks like the icon for this quest. You can't mine bedrock.
Don't let your eyes deceive you while diligently swinging away at it with your pickaxe. It's not going to work. I promise, on my honor as real news.

Being in a new environment can be challenging, as most of us are likely aware.

In an effort to mitigate frustration from UI troubles, listed below are some excerpts from my most helpful, less snarky pages that should serve you well.

Caveat; If I were to attempt to explain every possible interaction available to you, I wouldn't have any room in my pages for the §ofun§r quests, so this should be seen as a relatively brief primer and starter guide. You will find plenty of other lore pages, some of which will explain game concepts more in depth.

When in doubt, I recommend checking your controls, tooltips, or the quest you're working on if it requires a specific action.

§1§9§r§9Your Quest Book
§f§rFirst and foremost, while you can access the amazingly helpful knowledge I contain by using my physical form, I can also be accessed via hotkey (§1§d§5~§  §rby§r default), even if you lose me!

Next, while I try to be as succinct as possible and present everything on one page, you may need to §3scroll§r or use the §2arrows§r at the bottom of my pages to see an entry in full.
I apologize. I'm not as thin as I once was, as I'm now thick with knowledge!
Anyway, let's test the functions I mentioned on this entry.

§1§9Just Enough Items (JEI)
§rLet's move on to what will surely be your next best friend after me, the §5§rJEI interface§r.
This is the interface on the right (by default) when your inventory is open.
Its §2search bar§r allows you find just about anything in this multiverse.
Then, with a simple §5l-§r or §5r-click§r on item in question you can both determine how to craft it and what you can craft with it!

§mDon't say anything, but I love the JEI interface. <3§r
*cough*

Alright, back to everything else.

§1§9General Controls§r
You can exit almost any interface with §l§5esc§r.

Almost all other controls can be found, edited, and completely made a mess of via the "§l§2Controls§l§r" option in the main menu. Careful.

§WWhile we're on the topic of being careful, you can §3sneak/crouch§r by holding the assigned hotkey (§5shift§r by default) while you move.

§3Sneaking§r can help you avoid detection as well as prevent you from walking off the edge of the block you're on. Just be careful not to get hit by something, as it can easily push you over the edge to your demise.

Now, let's talk about how to §3sprint§r! You can do so by holding down the assigned hotkey (§5ctrl§r by default) while you move.

Just bear in mind that if you're too hungry or thirsty, §3sprinting§r won't be an option.

Wait! What good is all this sneaking and sprinting knowledge if you don't know how to move around in the first place?!
Your movements are mapped to §5w§r, §5a§r, §5s§r, §5d§r by default, essentially creating a left-handed set of arrow keys.

Aaand finally, certain items and machines have alternate functions when §5l-§r or §5r-clicking§r while holding §5shift§r or §5ctrl§r regardless of whether you're moving or not.

For example, you can §3equip§r and §3unequip§r items and gear by §5shift§r + §3§5l-clicking§r on them in your inventory. 

Now that you're likely feeling a little lost, let's talk about getting found.

§1Journey Map§r
You've got a map!
Yeah, you've got a minimap at the top right (default), but you can look at a larger version via hotkey (§1§5j§r by default).
Through this§r interface you can set and remove waypoints, see other nearby (or not-so-nearby players), and view details of the areas you've discovered.

This probably all seems like a lot, but I promise you'll get the hang of it as you fiddle around and explore this bizarre, cuboid reality.
Just remember, it's all about having a good time§m and avoiding unintended injuries, fatal mishaps, and unexpected creeper explosions§r.

This is it, your last tip! I'll try to simplify your quests by clearly labeling what you need to do to finish it at the bottom of each entry.
See below;

§nTask 1§r: Check the first box.
§nTask 2§r: Check the second box.

Over the course of your adventures, you're bound to come across many not-so-friendly entities.

It's truly a kill or be killed environment out here.

Time to show your mettle and reap the rewards.

§nTask 1§r: Kill a husk.
§nTask 2§r: Collect some rotten flesh.

*While the first task is to kill a husk, both husks and zombies, as well as a couple other unfriendlies, drop rotten flesh.

Congratulations! Your furnace is your first piece of significant "technology"!

There are a few different things you can do with a your fancy, new fire box. Let's try a couple now.

§nTask 1§r: Make some charcoal by putting logs in the furnace with fuel.
§nTask 2§r: Cook some food by putting it in the furnace with fuel.

*
There are many things that can fuel your furnace, some of which you may not want to put in there (tools, valuable items, etc.).
Different things have different burn rates, which you can see by holding §5shift§r while hovering over the thing in question with your cursor. Take a look at JEI and search for stuff like "leaves", "coal", "wood" to see the different burn times. If you don't remember JEI then be sure to re-read the early quest "§eSuch a User§r" for an overview of some key gameplay tools.

Logs are a good source of renewable early game fuel. Also keep your eyes open for surface deposits of coal - these indicate large coal veins beneath the surface.

By now, you should have an almost full set of leather armor.

While it's not the best defensive equipment you can get, it's better than nothing.

§nTask 1§r: Make some leather pants.

Bonus Task; Try to get that juicy peach into those tight new leather pants. ;D
^^ Not a real task. Don't overthink it.

Tables can be used to keep all kinds of things on it. They can also be used for the pure aesthetic of having tables. There are a variety of tables which can be made in this shard of the multiverse, so pick the one you like, and put something on it. Many tables can be placed next to each other to create larger tables. In case you have friends over, and they want to place things on the table.

People tend to have tables in places where they hang out.

Everything may be terrible but at least you can grill up some decent eats.

You can cook a variety of meats on this grill. Great for entertaining.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The revolution will not be televised
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
You can use this TV to display looped animated GIFs.

To set the GIFs, right click it with an empty hand. You can also turn it on and off from this display.

You can right click with the remote in the direction of the TV to change the channel. Shift right click to turn it off/on.

Sometimes walls are too much. Sometimes you just need a little visual barrier between parts of your home.

The paper wall can be used for this. Lightweight, easy to make with what can be found in the Block Rock Desert, and (most importantly) classy as all get out.
Flower pots are nice. You can put flowers in them and add a splash of color to your home, or your container.

You can put things you would like to show off in the item frame.  You can dye the frame if you would like.

You can place an item in the frame by holding the item in your hand and right clicking on the placed frame. You can then rotate the item by right clicking it. If you would like to get the item back then punch it.

Punching an empty frame will knock if off the wall. If you find yourself doing this often you may wish to speak to a therapist.

The reward for this quest is a painting. Upon placing it on the wall you get to choose the art.

Rugs can really tie the room together. Carpets are a decent simulacrum in this simulacrum of spectacles.

You can create carpet out of any color of wool. Once you get the right chisel, you can create patterened carpet too.

The reward is a door mat. Place it outside of your home. Upon doing so you will be prompted to write a welcome message.

betterquesting:10.name:8: All the pretty flags, all the pretty lights
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
The fairy lights mod gives you a bunch of pretty things you can make. Craft individual penant flags, bunting, tinsel, or lights. You can then combine them into a string.  You can even mix and match different colors of the same type.


You can then string them together using two iron ingots and a piece of string. The iron ingots go in the upper right and left of a crafting table. The string goes in the middle. Place up to six bits (lights, penant flags, etc) in the lower six slots. This will give you a single string of flags/lights/whatever that can stretch for up to 32 blocks.

To place the strings, right click on a block (most work for this purpose). You can then right click on a second block to complete the placement. 

You can turn the lights on/off by right clicking on them with an empty hand.

You can tighten the slack of the string by right clicking them with a stick. You can increase the slack by right clicking with a piece of string.

Great for fire houses and bat caves alike - the pole!

You can create these bat poles in batches of sixteen by stacking three blocks of the appropriate material on top of each other in a crafting grid. Right click to place the pole on a flat surface. You can then place more poles on top of it or you can right click on the already placed pole with another pole to extend the height. If you place a torch on top of your first pole, it will be raised as the pole grows to make for a neat beacon. If you break the bottom pole, the whole stack will shift down by one.

If you jump onto a pole (don't miss - especially if it goes down to bedrock!) you will grab on and slide down the pole. You will spin around in the direction your camera is facing. You can hop off the pole at any time by pressing the duck key (defaults to left shift). You can kinda climb back up but it's incredibly slow.

Redstone poles are special. If you build them on top of a redstone block you will travel up not down. Note that while on the surface this may seem like a stripper pole remember that Minecraft is the least erotic game ever.

The other poles are just like iron poles but you will travel faster. Note that a single iron bar will act as an iron pole, just less classy.

Elevators make travelling up and down your rapidly expanding home much easier. These elevators come in multiple colors and in a rotating and non rotating variety. The rotating variety will always ensure you are pointing in a consistent direction when arriving on the floor.

Elevators have a max vertical range of 20 blocks and must be vertically aligned. There may be no more than four solid blocks between floors.

The Cooking for Blockheads mod gives you all kinds of blocks you can use to make your kitchen more usable. The blocks, when placed together, are easily accessible. The key block is the Cooking Table. This block ends up connected to the other blocks and can make use of their functionality from it's interface. You can dye these blocks to make the kitchen of your dreams.

* The fridge (can stack and can be dyed) is used to store ingredients. Shift right click to open and look at the contents like the indecisive punk you are.
* The oven will cook food. You need to supply it with fuel.
* The counters and cabinets can be used to store ingredients.
* The tool rack can be used to store various cooking implements from Pam's Harvestcraft
* The spice rack can be used to store spices

The Arhictects Sawmill is used to create specialty blocks. These blocks include columns, window frames, railings for stair cases, and for a some reason a sphere. You can use pretty much any block in this but note that flammable blocks sadly to not retair their flammability.

There is a limited set of speciality blocks available through the Blockcraftery mod. These block frames can be placed down and then have a block applied to them. The non-reinforced version is flammable.

The Chisel & Bits mod breaks up blocks into a 16x16x16 pixel grid. You can then make use of these pixels to make more fine art in Minecraft. When holding the chisel, press the alt (default keybinding) key to get a radial menu of options.

You can make some bags as well to hold all the bits you will end up with. It will be a lot.

Using the Chisel (from the Chisel mod, as opposed to one of the other chisels) it is possible to easily change the texture of blocks before placing them into the world.  You can use this to get access to variations on textures (cracked vs worn stone for example). The mod also supports some specific sets of blocks which can be crafted and reskinned including Factory Bocks, and Future Blocks.

This journal entry has information on the three kinds of chisels available for use.

Most plants, magical or otherwise, can only be planted in dirt that is both wet and also tilled. You are going to need some actual dirt (not just sand), a hoe, and a bucket of water.

While you are at it, may as well try and harvest some of those arid gardens that are everywhere. Might be something good in there.

The watering can you get as a reward may be filled by holding down the right mouse botton while looking at a water block. Right click over crowing crops to increase the speed at which they grow a little bit. Not quite as good as a sprinkler, but it's a start.

And being in a garden just feels good.

The Field Manual, which you received as a quest reward for making a pickaxe, contains information on how to find Ore in the Tribes That May Be multiverse. You may have noticed surface deposits of various ores - coal, limonite, and azurite are all common. There are less common ones as well - gold and cinabar as examples. When you find these surface deposits it means that somewhere below is a (likely quite large) deposit of ore.

The prospectors pick, although it needs a decent amount of iron, can make finding the ore deposits underground much easier. The Field Manual contains details on how to use it. A general mining strategy for someone who has a mining pick could be...

1) Find a surface deposit
2) Start digging down to bedrock. Use a staircase method, taking 90' turns periodically, try to stay near where you found the surface deposit.
3) As you go down, right click on something with the prospectors pick. If it says that there are no deposits go back to your last 90' turn and go the other way.
4) Keep checking JEI to see the Y level of where you can expect to find the ore. Once you get to that level, start branching out until you find the deposit. You shouldn't ever have to go more than a dozen or so blocks in any direction - assuming you stayed roughtly under the surface deposits.

If you don't yet have a mining pick, the strategy can be loosely the same. The important part is to make sure you are within a few blocks of the surface deposit as you dig down. Without the prospectors pick, if you do not find the vein on your first pass down to the y-level it's found at, you may wish to start digging corridors out ten or so blocks periodically or branch mining.

If you don't know what JEI is then make sure to carefully read the Such a User quest as it covers the usage of such neccesary things as the map and JEI.

Find a nice (permanent, it's a pain to move) place for your smeltery. The Materials and You book, which you should already have, contains information on how to build the smeltery and what the different pieces do. I'd recommend taking a look through that book because the smeltery can be a bit confusing the first time.

Start by creating a 3x3 bottom layer of smeltery bricks in your floor. Now, create the first layer of the walls. The walls should not be placed on top of the floor - you should end up with a 3x3x2 space within the smeltery. Place the tank on the bottom layer, the controller and a drain on the top layer.

Once you have created the casting table place it under the drain and place the faucet on to the drain. Until you expand your smeltery, you will need to swap the casting table and basin depending on whether you want parts or blocks.

You will need a metal bucket to transfer lava from the world (if you haven't found any on the surface there is plenty underground) to the tank.

There are a lot of things that end up in a lot of bins that you need to remember about. At least we can make the bins a bit larger, and keep more things in them. There are several layers of expanded bins which can be made by either crafting one of the bins surrounded by ingots, or by right clicking on an existing bin with an upgrade. You can craft the upgrades by surrounding a piece of planking with ingots.

The next thing we get into after larger bins is moving items between things!

Let's plant our first garden! You will need some dirt. 24 blocks of dirt is a good starting point. Make a 5x5 plot of dirt, with a single space empty in the middle. Fill this space with water - it should hydrate soil up to a radius about four blocks around. This is the baseline amount of water we can provide to a garden.

Use the hoe on the dirt to turn it into farmland. This is done by §5right clicking§r the dirt. You can then plant seeds in this farmland - almost every kind of seed needs farmland to grow. Make sure to put a tall fence around your crops - tumbleweeds, monsters jumping, and other hazards can cause the farmland to turn back to dirt - which will cause you to lose crops.

Early game methods of increasing the growth rate are using bone meal (see JEI for how to make this) and the watering can.

There are only a handful of seeds that you can find in the Block Rock Desert so we'll let you choose from some luxuries in the quest rewards.

Wonder how far we will need to go to find more seeds....

In order to craft, let alone grow, fancier mystical seeds you will need to convert your Inferium Essence into more advanced kinds of essence. This is done by use of an infusion crystal. These have a limited number of uses and may not be recharged. To use, simply include it in a recipe that requires it in a crafting table.

Craft an infusion crystal and then use it to craft a T2 Crafting Seed and T2 Inferium Seed
Fire Essence, a tier 2 crop, is used in crafting a variety of things which are not natively found in the Block Rock Desert. You will probably want to get a good crop of it going.

Nothing is worse than digging around in a nearly empty cardboard box marked "not drugs" trying to find the infusion crystal that has more than one charge left.

Let's make an infinite infusion crystal!

You will need a lot of essence.

Using sprinkers can help speed up the growth rate of plants with a radius of about three blocks. It must be placed over a water block to function. It will not go through walls. Even crops which are being sufficiently watered will not grow if they are not in season.

In order to grow all crops even though you are in the desert and it's basically always summer, you are going to need some greenhouse glass. Here is some to get you started, but you are going to want more.

Growth accelerators will look for things growing up to sixty four blocks above and give it a boost. There is a cumulative effect when you stack them. This can have an accelerating affect on your crop growth, and stacks with sprinklers.

Drinking only water gets boring after a while. We need it to survive, but it's just so plain. You can tell you are severely dehydrated when water tastes really really good.

Make some cactus fruit juice and use it to get some flavor into you as well as replenish your precious bodily fluids.

There are several food items which provide minimal to no basic nutrition but will keep you hydrated.

There are also some food items which make you more thirsty so watch out for that too.

We are going to need steel. Lots of steel. The first step down this path of industry is creating enough Coke Bricks that you can make a Coke Oven.

We are looking for two products here - creosote, which is used to create treated wood - a common engineering component, and coal coke - which will go in our blast furnace to refine steel from iron.

Create 21 Coke Bricks.

We are going to make a hammer today. The hammer mines out a 3x3 section of space and makes a decent weapon against skeletons.

 Before doing so, let's collect all the pieces we need.

* A Tinkers Workshop including
  * A built and working smeltery filled with lava and a casting table attached.
* A Tough Tool Rod pattern
* Casts for Tough Tool Binding, Hammer Head, and Large Plates

Throw enough iron ore in the smeltery to craft all the parts. Fourteen blocks of iron ore should do it - the smeltery has a doubling effect on ore. Unlike plain furnaces, one piece of ore results in two ingots worth of material which can be used. It will take a few moments to melt the iron - different materials have different melting points.

Once the iron is melted, make the parts. Place the tough tool binding on your casting table and right click on the faucet. Repeat for the hammer head and the two large plates. You can create the tough tool rod in the part station.

Any tool which incorporates parts from the smeltery needs to be assembled in the Tool Forge.

A mattock is a great versatile tool. You can use it to chop wood and deal with softer blocks such as dirt and sand.

We are going to make a mattock using our brand new Tinkers Workshop. We are going to use wood and flint for it, so you will need to find some gravel and chop down some trees. You will need four pieces of flint and two planks.

Make the stencils for the shovel head, axe head, and tool rod using the Stencil Table. You can keep stencils in a Pattern Chest.

These stencils can be used in the Part Builder, along with the appropriate material, to make the individual parts. Make a flint axe head, a flint shovel head, and a wooden tool rod. Each material has it's own passive modifier effect. Wood has the "Ecological" effect which results in tools being repaired over time. Check out the Materials and You book for information on each type of material.

Tools may be repaired in the tool station by combining them with whichever material is most present in the tool. You can also craft Sharpening Kits which may be used to repair tools in the field.

In order to make metal parts on the casting table you need casts and a tool forge. Single use casts can be made out of clay. Multi use casts can be made out of aluminum. You can keep casts in Parts Chests but note you can't mix stencils/clay/normal casts in the same chest.

Throw some clay in your smeltery. You will need four pieces for this.

Craft a tough binding and large plate in your tool station, it doesn't matter what material it's made out of, but err on the cheap side, it will be consumed during this process.

Place the sharpening kit on the casting table by right clicking. Right click on the faucet you have installed on a drain above the casting basin. Some clay will come out and you will end up with a single-use cast of a repair kit. Now place the large plate on the casting basin and pour the rest of the clay in.

You can use the casting basin to make the blocks needed for the tool forge.

The smeltery can be used to combine materials and create alloys. The first alloy we will make is aluminum brass as it can be used to create casts which do not get consumed. It takes a 3:1 ratio of Aluminum (found in Bauxite deposits) and Copper (found in Malachite and Azurite deposits). Remember the doubling effect of the smeltery on ore when creating alloys.

Put all the materials in to the smeltery and wait for them to melt. Once that has occured then you need to wait for the alloying to happen. Once that has occured you can use resulting alloy to cast things. You should start by making a plate cast.

Sometimes you want to make a thing and you are far from your crafting table and you don't want to just make another crafting table and leave it where you are because leaving no trace is real.

The Crafting Table on a Stick is for you. It's like a crafting table, but on a stick, and you can keep it in your backpack or on your toolbelt.

Time to make your coke oven. This is a 3x3x3 structure with an (aesthetically appealing) front. Once you have assembled your 3x3x3 coke oven using the Coke Bricks the center block of the side you want to be the front with your Engineers Hammer.

You can empty it of creosote as it gets filled using buckets. Check out the "I Can't Help My Shelf" quest line to learn how to automate this.

Time to make some steel. You will need 21 Blast Furnace Bricks. You can eventually upgrade your blast furnace but for now the basic one will do.

You are going to need blaze rods.

Certain traders will have them it for sale, and they show up as loot, are occasionally dropped by ((some flower in brd)), and you can find them off blazes when you travel to the nether.

Assemble the Blast Furnace the same way as the Coke Oven. It's a 3x3x3 cube, and then right click with the engineers hammer to assemble it. It must be fueled with Coal Coke and you can use it to convert iron ingots or blocks into steel ingots or blocks.

You have probably been grateful for your trusty tank which you have no doubt been keeping a decent amount of delicious water in. The wooden and metal barrels only get us so far. Sometimes you want to store a lot of milk. The first forray into this level of liquid storage is the Basic Fluid Tank.

Craft a basic fluid tank. As a reward, you will receive some higher volume pipes.

You can talk to other players by bringing up the chat bar (the default key is "T") and typing your message. You can only talk to people who are within shouting distance - about 180 blocks. And you can only talk to these people when you are all online at the same time.

For other things, there is a mailbox. You can create your very own mailbox and then craft envelopes and packages to send written letters or items to your friends.

Sometimes you want to stop filling your drawers with junk. The Void Upgrade will continue accepting items past it's storage limit and instead of storing them simply remove them from existence.

This upgrade, and the storage upgrade, are among a handful of upgrades which may be crafted for Storage Drawers. Use JEI to take a look at all of the different upgrades.

Drawers are cool but you know whats cooler? Not having to visit each drawer in order to empty your inventory.

Also being able to have your growing industry output feed directly into (let alone take from) your growing library of drawers.

The Drawer Controller will connect to any drawer it is contiguously connected to via other drawers (or trim) within a 12 block radius. Right clicking on the upper portion (the bit with a downward facing chevron) will place whatever is in your hand in the appropriate drawer. Double right cicking will drain your inventory. You can attach bits of automation and tech to the drawer controller to access the full inventory.

Chances are you will need to use Dark Oak Trim (constructed from Black Kauraki planks) to create the controller.

Compacting drawers are great because they handle auto conversion between resources that support it. Iron ingots are also accessible as nuggets and blocks, emeralds and diamonds are also stored as blocks.

When used in conjuntion with a drawer controller, every variant of resource will be exposed as within the inventory.

There are a handful of keys which may be crafted that control the specific behavior of drawers.

* The Quantify Key shows the quantity of the stored item on the drawer face.
* The Drawer Key sets/removes a filter on the drawer based on what is currently stored .
* Personal Key can lock/unlock your drawers so that other players are not able to interact with them.
* The Concealment Key hides/shows the contents from displaying on the drawer face.

Using the Armor Station you can create armor using a wide variety of materials, similar to what we can do with tools and weapons.

Create some casts, using clay if you haven't yet found aluminum, and make yourself the pieces for a nice helment. Assemble it in the armor station.

And then make a nice helmet. Give it a good name and treat it well and it will be with you for a while.

We use our Tinkers workshop for tools, armor, and weapons. Let's start by making a sword. You make the base parts and we'll give you some fancy hand guard choices. Take a refresher look through Materials and You for information about each type of sword. Remember that when assembling weapons (and tools) that make use of metals you need to use the tool forge.

You will continue to collect books as you learn more about this world. Some of these books will help you build things, some of them will help you enchant things, some will help you remember things, and at least one will result in your agonizing death.

You can use book shelves to store these books, along with other forms of media you may create or find.

You are going to want to grow most of your crops in a greenhouse. This is both to keep them protected from the elements (playa dust and tumbleweeds, let alone creepers, can interfere with your garden) but also to ensure that you can grow any crop any time of the year. You will want the greenhouse glass at least 3 blocks above your farmland. I don't think there is a max height.

You are going to need glass, which can be made by smelting sand. You are going to also need cyan dye, which can be made by combining green dye and lapis lazulli.

betterquesting:10.name:8: There is a Season for That
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Not every crop can grow every time of the year. While you can make a proper green house in order to avoid this, you can also do seasonal planting. If you make a Season Clock you can know what part of the season you are in. Not the season itself.

I don't know, it's confusing. You should just make a greenhouse.

The scythe is a much better tool than the hoe, or your hands, for harvesting crops. Double right click with it on crops and it will harvest everything ready in a 3x3 area. Normal right click will harvest like normal.

You can also use it as a non terrible weapon and/or part of a death cosplay.

Combine the tool rods, the binding, and the iron scythe head you already have in a tool forge to make a scythe.
The third tier of resource seeds allows you to to start growing stuff like iron and glowstone.
The fourth level of resource growing nets you valuable resources such as gold, steel, and electrum.

The crossbow is pretty rad and let's you reach out and tap your enemies without getting in range. Given the multitude of upgrades and modifiers you can make to your Tinkers items, it can be quite customizable too. The process for building the crossbow bolt isn't the most intuituve, so make sure to take a look at the bolt section of the Tools chapter in Materials and You.

Make most of the pieces you'll need for the crossbow, and then select one of the fancy pieces as a quest reward.
Diamonds are shiny, and used in a lot of crafting. The fourth level of resource growing gets you things like Diamonds and Emeralds.
There are only so many seeds you can find in the Block Rock Desert. You should try and find someone who sells seeds. At least one of these villages should have someone...

Luggage is a companion who will gobble up any items around it. Luggage will follow you around and act as a medium sized chest. Luggage is pretty much invincible from enemy damage but you probably don't want luggage to fall off the world or intro a pit of lava. Luggage will follow you around quite quickly once you get a few dozen blocks away. You can pick luggage up with a "Shift-Right Click".

You are going to be moving around a lot, and you are probably going to not want to always sleep outside. There are a variety of portable tents you can make. Once you place these tents down for the first time, a small "pocket dimension" is created for the interior. Things you place inside will stay there. If you place a bed in your tent and sleep in there, it will act as your spawn. You can also pick up your tent and take it with you as well.

We are going to start with a bedouin tent but there are several to choose from. Look for items from the "Nomadic Tents" mod in JEI.

You are going to need a lot of sisal (can be found in desert gardens) in order to make a lot of string in order to make a lot of cotton in order to make a handful of bedouin tent pieces. Use these five bedouin tent pieces to construct a small bedouin tent.

And a Tent Mallet. We are going to need another hammer.

Nomadic Tents act as small homes which you may pack up and bring with you on adventures. They are easily upgradeable and provide a bit of protection at night from the outside world.

To place your tent, place it down in small clearing. It needs 5x5 unobstructed space. The tent will then be framed out, and you can use (right click) the Tent Mallet on the frame to build it. Once you find gold, you can make an upgraded tent mallet to do this in a single click.

You can enter/exit your tent by walking through or right clicking on the door. You can pack up your tent by right clicking on the door (when outside) with the Tent Mallet.

There are a variety of eclectic bicycle like creations which the Animal Bikes mod provides. To start, we are going to create a Spider Bike. While not very fast, it can climb walls. Each Animal Bike has it's own special ability. 

To use the bike, place it down (with right click) and then hop on it (with right click). To dismount, press shift. You can pick the bike back up by using shift-right click. Note that you can only use the bike a few dozen times or so before it will break.

While the hang glider may not be the most useful on it's own in the desert (depending on what kind of structures you find), there are other dimensions in which it is incredibly useful. To use it, simply make sure it is active and then right click to activate it. You can speed up a little bit by holding shift. If you right click again it will deactivate (you probably want to be on the ground for that).

You can modify the wheels and engine for vehicles by placing them on a jack. The jack can be placed on the ground like any other structure. To place a vehicle on a jack, shift right click it to pick it up, and then shift right click on the jack to place it. You can open up the interface by right clicking on the jack with your wrench. From this interface you can replace the engine and wheels for your ride. The higher tiers of engines allow the vehicle to travel faster, and the different kinds of wheels are optimized for different surfaces.

You can also repair your vehicle when it is on the jack by right clicking on it while holding the hammer.

Still going to need gas...
You can create (and then dye) spray cans which you can use to paint your vehicles. These spray cans have a finite number of uses.
By right clicking on a vehicle with a key you can stop people from driving off with your ride. They can still carry it off, because this is still a video game. But they won't get far on foot....

To start our inter dimensional voyage we are going to need an ink mixer and a book binder. As a reward you get a handful of either book stands or lecterns. The various link and descriptive books that you will create, that will allow you to travel between ages and worlds, should always be placed in these before reading.

Otherwise they will end up on the ground and can be damaged by rain or picked up by unsavory characters. These created dimensions can be very dangerous and if you are not careful you could end up stuck there for ever.

There are so many things to store, so many ways to organize them, and did we mention there are so many things to store.

Sometimes you won't want to empty a chest/bin in order to make it larger. When you find yourself in this position, consider making a chest upgrade. This will convert a storage chest/bin into the next tier.

Sometimes you just want to store a single item. Using the tiny chest you get as a reward, you can do just that.

There are so many storage options, remember you can search through JEI to see all of them. Always remember you can check the entry under "Gameplay" in your journal for a refresher.

The first of many upgrades is the Laboratory Furnace. You can improve your existing furnace a little bit and make it more efficient. Both in terms of fuel usage, but also repeat usage. This furnace is provided by the Engineers Decor mod, which helps lend a bit to the aesthetic and functionality of the world.

You harvested something! Many things which you harvest are edible. Some are meant for industry.

Many things which you harvest can be converted into seeds in a crafting table.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Block is not always what it seems
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
You can use the blockcraftery blocks to make structures that are then textured based on another block. There are a variety of blocks, along with some door options. Great for adding some non-ninety-degree angles to your creations, or for making hidden doors. While the architects workbench should work for most cases, there are some blocks which cannot be fed through it. In those cases, blockcraftery blocks should work.

The normal variant is flamable. The reinforced variant should hold up against fire and most explosions.

Thr trowel is used to rapidly place down a random distribution of blocks. It is great for building with chisel based bricks to add cracked/mossy variants. To use it, place it in a hotbar row with the blocks you want it to pull from. Simply right click with the trowel where you want to place a block. It will randomly place a block, weighted based on how many slots have the same block.

There are a variety of doors available to create but even then sometimes that isn't enough. Maybe you want it made out of magic wood and gold rimmed.

For this, you need the door factory. You can customize the frame and upper/lower panels, along with a how the door opens and operates.
Whats this, magic beans? If scuttlebutt is true, then I should mostly get useful stuff out of these. These annual plants should last a lifetime, if treated properly.

We are getting closer to escaping this endless desert, even if only for a moment.

Start by making (or finding) some ink bottles. These get placed in the ink mixer, in the upper left slot. The lower left slot takes paper. The ink mixer is used to create "link pages" which you then craft into a variety of mystcraft related books.

Let's start with a link book and a (blank and completely random) descriptive book.

The link book (unliked at start) is used to create a link to a specific dimension. Once you've crafted it, right click with it on the ground (or any nearby non-interactive object) will link it to the dimension you are in. This is how you will return home from strange dimensions when voyaging. You can craft a unlinked link book by combining a single link page and a single piece of leather in any crafting grid.

The descriptive book is how we travel to other dimensions.  Be warned, even carefully crafted dimensions (which we did not just do) can be very hazardous to your health.

Not every hammer is created by slapping some metal together. For fancier things, we will need metal plates. There are two ways they may be made by hand - with a hammer (although this is hard on the hammer) and in a smeltery with the right plate.

Time to go. If you are careful, you will make it back. If you aren't, it'll be a while before you see this desert again. Always remember that when you are using mystcraft books to leave them in a lectern or bookstand. And always remember to bring a link book that is linked back to your home dimension.

The first time you go to a new dimension, it's generally also a good idea to bring plenty of snacks and enough supplies to make a little basecamp away from home. And plenty of water.

Place the bookstand or lectern down in a secure location. Place the book on it by right clicking. You can pick the book back up by shift right clicking later. When you are ready to go, right click the placed book and click on the colored square on the first page.

Eventually you will be able to write your own ages and go to custom dimeensions, but for now it will be completely random.

betterquesting:10.name:8: I Just Can't Help My Shelf
betterquesting:10.desc:8: It's not easy having a good time. The amount of logistics involved are staggering. The storage concerns alone are enough to fill a Big Book with.

There are may ways to perish and to be comfortable in this multiverse.

It's important to find pleasure in the simple things.

This is my tool. There are many like it, but this one is mine.

My tool is my best friend. It is my life.
It ain't a real party without some sweet tunes.
Well, you finally made it to the desert. But why? I guess try to not die.

We've gotten by up until now with being able to extract sunk carbon in the least efficient way possible. Let's try and do better and not make this world more of a hellscape.

If we are going to expand and ultimately end up at our fully automated anarchist queer block utopia then we are going to need to power ourselves through it. There are several ways of generating power with varying levels of power output and need to pay attention. It's possible to move power via wires, or via batteries.

You may find in some cases that you do not need full power infrastructure for smaller outposts, but if you do, the wires you create can be run throughout the realm without any worry about loaded chunks.
There are plenty of ways to navigate this world. And remember there are more worlds than these. And you will go to them. Try to not die.
You are going to need to eat something eventually. And you will probably. eventually, want something that is not water to drink.
Any sufficiently advanced magic is indistinguishable from technology.
The more you explore, the greater the danger. Do what you can to protect yourself, whichever way seems right to you.
